453","1332":"1332","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","about 1412":"circa 1412","about 1332":"circa 1332","6 August 1402":"6 augustus 1402","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wath upon Dearne, South Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wath upon Dearne, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England","Wath upon Dearne, Yorkshire, England":"Wath upon Dearne, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1332–about 1412":"about 1332–about 1412","1320–1364":"1320–1364","1332–1412":"1332–1412","1358–1432":"1358–1432","–Male":"Deceased","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","26 April 1402":"26 April 1402","1337":"1337","Abt 1360":"about 1360","1358":"1358","1412":"1412","1300":"1300","1432":"1432","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","about 1412":"about 1412","about 1332":"about 1332","6 August 1402":"6 August 1402","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Wath upon Dearne, South Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wath upon Dearne, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England","Wath upon Dearne, Yorkshire, England":"Wath upon Dearne, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fleming","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, from Middle English <i>fleming</i>. The word reflects a Norman French form of Old French <i>flamanc</i> ‘Fleming’, from the stem <i>flam-</i> + the ancient Germanic suffix <i>-ing</i>. In the Middle Ages there was considerable commercial intercourse between England and the Netherlands, particularly in the wool trade, and many Flemish weavers and dyers settled in England. This surname is also common in south and east Scotland and in Ireland, where it is sometimes found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["English: ethnic name from Middle English <i>Fla(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":5,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":50,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas de Fleming II was born about 1332, in Wath upon Dearne, Yorkshire, England as the son of Thomas Fleming I. He had at least 2 sons. He died about 1412, in Croston, Lancashire, England, at the age of 82."},"et":{"about 1332–about 1412":"umbes 1332–umbes 1412","1320–1364":"1320–1364","1332–1412":"1332–1412","1358–1432":"1358–1432","–Male":"Surnud","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","26 April 1402":"26 aprill 1402","1337":"1337","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1358":"1358","1412":"1412","1300":"1300","1432":"1432","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","about 1412":"umbes 1412","about 1332":"umbes 1332","6 August 1402":"6 august 1402","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wath upon Dearne, South Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wath upon Dearne, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, Engla